Explanation and Important Notes:

  1. Vagrantfile Structure:

    • This Vagrantfile defines four virtual machines: ansible-controller, k8s-master, k8s-worker1, and k8s-worker2.
    • Each VM is assigned a static IP address on a private network (192.168.56.0/24).
    • The ansible-controller VM is configured to run an Ansible playbook.

  2. Kubernetes Installation (Shell Provisioning):

    • The k8s-master and worker VMs use shell provisioning to install Kubernetes components (kubelet, kubeadm, kubectl).
    • Crucially, swapoff -a and disabling swap in /etc/fstab are included, as Kubernetes requires swap to be disabled.

  3. Ansible Provisioning:

    • The ansible-controller VM uses the Ansible provisioner to execute the ansible/playbook.yml playbook.
    • The ansible/inventory file will need to be created, and contain the host information.
    • extra_vars are used to pass the IP addresses of the Kubernetes nodes to the Ansible playbook.

  4. Ansible Playbook and Inventory (You Must Create These):

    • ansible/inventory:

      Ini, TOML
      [k8s_master]
k8s-master ansible_host=192.168.56.11

[k8s_workers]
k8s-worker1 ansible_host=192.168.56.12
k8s-worker2 ansible_host=192.168.56.13

[k8s_cluster:children]
k8s_master
k8s_workers

    • ansible/playbook.yml:

      • This is where the actual Kubernetes cluster setup logic goes. You'll need to create this file. It would contain the tasks to initialize the master node using kubeadm init, join the worker nodes using kubeadm join, and install a network plugin (like Calico or Flannel).
      • Example tasks that should be included in the playbook:
        • Initialize the master node: kubeadm init --pod-network-cidr=10.244.0.0/16 --apiserver-advertise-address=192.168.56.11
        • Copy the kubeconfig file from the master to the ansible controller.
        • Join the worker nodes: kubeadm join 192.168.56.11:6443 --token <token> --discovery-token-ca-cert-hash sha256:<hash> (The token and hash are obtained from the kubeadm init output).
        • Install a network plugin: kubectl apply -f <network-plugin.yaml>
        • Copy the kubeconfig to your local machine, if desired.

  5. Network Plugin:

    • You'll need to choose and install a network plugin (Calico, Flannel, etc.) in your Ansible playbook. The example playbook tasks shows where it is installed.

  6. VirtualBox:

    • This Vagrantfile is configured for VirtualBox. Ensure you have VirtualBox installed.

  7. Resource Allocation:

    • The Master node is allocated more memory due to the control plane services.
    • Adjust memory and CPU allocations as needed for your environment.

  8. Security:

    • This setup is for development and testing. Do not use it for production without proper security hardening.

How to Use:

  1. Save the Vagrantfile.
  2. Create the ansible directory and the ansible/inventory and ansible/playbook.yml files.
  3. vagrant up
  4. The VMs will be created, and the Ansible playbook will configure the Kubernetes cluster.
  5. After the playbook finishes, you can use kubectl on the Ansible controller (or your local machine, if you copied the kubeconfig) to interact with the cluster.

Absolutely. Here's the content you should place in the inventory file and a basic structure for the playbook.yml file, along with explanations:

1. ansible/inventory:

Ini, TOML
[k8s_master]
k8s-master ansible_host=192.168.56.11

[k8s_workers]
k8s-worker1 ansible_host=192.168.56.12
k8s-worker2 ansible_host=192.168.56.13

[k8s_cluster:children]
k8s_master
k8s_workers
  • [k8s_master]: This defines a group named k8s_master containing the Kubernetes master node.
  • k8s-master ansible_host=192.168.56.11: This specifies the hostname (k8s-master) and the IP address (192.168.56.11) of the master node.
  • [k8s_workers]: This defines a group named k8s_workers containing the Kubernetes worker nodes.
  • k8s-worker1 ansible_host=192.168.56.12 and k8s-worker2 ansible_host=192.168.56.13: These lines specify the hostnames and IP addresses of the worker nodes.
  • [k8s_cluster:children]: This creates a group named k8s_cluster that includes the k8s_master and k8s_workers groups as its children. This allows you to target all nodes in the cluster with a single group name.

2. ansible/playbook.yml:

YAML
---
- hosts: k8s_master
  become: true
  tasks:
    - name: Initialize Kubernetes master
      command: kubeadm init --pod-network-cidr=10.244.0.0/16 --apiserver-advertise-address={{ k8s_master_ip }}
      register: kubeadm_init_output

    - name: Create .kube directory
      become_user: vagrant
      file:
        path: $HOME/.kube
        state: directory
        mode: '0755'

    - name: Copy kubeconfig to vagrant user
      become_user: vagrant
      copy:
        src: /etc/kubernetes/admin.conf
        dest: $HOME/.kube/config
        remote_src: yes
        owner: vagrant
        group: vagrant
        mode: '0600'

    - name: Get join command
      set_fact:
        join_command: "{{ kubeadm_init_output.stdout_lines | select('match', 'kubeadm join') | first }}"

- hosts: k8s_workers
  become: true
  tasks:
    - name: Join Kubernetes worker nodes
      command: "{{ join_command }}"
      register: kubeadm_join_output

- hosts: k8s_master
  become: true
  tasks:
    - name: Apply Calico network plugin
      command: kubectl apply -f https://docs.projectcalico.org/manifests/calico.yaml

Explanation of playbook.yml:

  • - hosts: k8s_master: This section targets the k8s_master group.
  • become: true: This runs the tasks with root privileges.
  • tasks:: This section defines the tasks to be executed.
    • kubeadm init: Initializes the Kubernetes master node. The k8s_master_ip variable is used to set the apiserver-advertise-address.
    • register: kubeadm_init_output: Stores the output of the kubeadm init command.
    • Create kube config directory and copy config file: copies the kubernetes admin.conf file to the vagrant users home directory, so kubectl can be used.
    • set_fact: join_command: Extracts the kubeadm join command from the kubeadm init output.
  • - hosts: k8s_workers: This section targets the k8s_workers group.
    • command: "{{ join_command }}": Executes the kubeadm join command obtained from the master node.
  • - hosts: k8s_master: This section targets the k8s_master group.
    • Apply Calico network plugin: Applies the Calico network plugin to the cluster. This is essential for pod networking.

Important Notes:

  • Network Plugin: Calico is used in this example. You can replace it with another plugin (Flannel, Cilium, etc.) by changing the URL in the kubectl apply command.
  • k8s_master_ip, k8s_worker1_ip, k8s_worker2_ip: These variables are passed from your Vagrantfile.
  • Security: This is a basic setup for development and testing. Production deployments require proper security hardening.
  • Error Handling: The playbook lacks robust error handling. You should add error checking and handling for production use.
  • Kubectl: This playbook assumes kubectl is installed on the master node, since the vagrantfile installs it.
  • Join Token and Hash: The join token and hash are handled automatically by the playbook.
  • Idempotency: Ansible playbooks aim for idempotency, meaning running them multiple times should produce the same result. The kubeadm commands are generally idempotent.

when will we run playbook.yaml

The playbook.yml will run automatically as part of the vagrant up process, but only on the ansible-controller VM, and after that VM has been created and provisioned.

Here's a breakdown of the sequence:

  1. vagrant up: You initiate the Vagrant environment.  
  2. VM Creation: Vagrant creates the four VMs (ansible-controller, k8s-master, k8s-worker1, k8s-worker2) in the order they are defined in the Vagrantfile.
  3. Shell Provisioning: For the k8s-master, k8s-worker1, and k8s-worker2 VMs, the shell provisioner runs first. This installs the necessary Kubernetes components (kubelet, kubeadm, kubectl) and disables swap.
  4. Ansible Provisioning: Once the ansible-controller VM is created and the shell provisioning (if any) is complete, the ansible_local provisioner kicks in.
    • Vagrant copies the ansible directory from your host machine to /home/vagrant/ansible inside the ansible-controller VM.
    • Ansible is installed in the guest vm.  
    • Ansible then runs the playbook.yml file from within the guest vm.
  5. Kubernetes Cluster Configuration: The playbook.yml contains the tasks to initialize the Kubernetes master, join the worker nodes, and install the network plugin. These tasks are executed on the respective VMs as defined in the Ansible inventory and playbook.

In summary:

  • The playbook.yml is run by the Ansible provisioner after the ansible-controller VM is up and running.
  • The playbook will run automatically during the vagrant up process, you do not need to manually run it.

Important Considerations:

  • Order of Operations: The order of operations is important. The shell provisioning must complete before the Ansible playbook runs, as the playbook relies on the Kubernetes components being installed.
  • Ansible Local: We are using ansible_local, so ansible is run inside the guest machine. This is very important.
  • Vagrant Synced Folders: The synced folder is used to get the ansible files into the guest machine.

You're absolutely correct to point that out. While the ansible_local provisioner automatically runs the playbook.yml during vagrant up, it might not be immediately obvious from the command-line output. Also, the order of operations can be a bit subtle.

Here's a more detailed explanation and some clarifications:

How ansible_local Runs the Playbook:

  • Implicit Execution: The ansible_local provisioner is designed to run the Ansible playbook as part of the VM provisioning process. You don't need to explicitly execute an ansible-playbook command.
  • Vagrant's Internal Logic: Vagrant handles the behind-the-scenes work of copying the Ansible files to the VM and invoking Ansible.

Ensuring Dependencies and Order:

  • Vagrant's Provisioning Order: Vagrant executes provisioners in the order they are defined in the Vagrantfile.
  • Shell Provisioning First: The shell provisioners for the Kubernetes master and worker nodes run before the Ansible provisioner on the ansible-controller. This ensures that kubeadm, kubelet, and kubectl are installed before the Ansible playbook attempts to use them.
  • Sequential VM Creation: Vagrant creates the VMs sequentially. Vagrant will create the master and workers first, and then the controller. So, the master and workers will have their pre-requisites installed before the ansible controller runs the playbook.
  • Ansible's Dependency Handling: Within the Ansible playbook, you can further control the order of tasks and handle dependencies using Ansible's features (e.g., wait_for, block, rescue).

Why You Might Not See an Explicit Command:

  • Vagrant's Abstraction: Vagrant abstracts away some of the underlying commands to simplify the provisioning process.
  • Provisioner's Internal Execution: The ansible_local provisioner runs Ansible internally, and its output is integrated into Vagrant's output.

How to Monitor Playbook Execution:

  • Vagrant's Output: Vagrant will display the output of the Ansible playbook in your terminal. You should see the tasks being executed and any output from those tasks.
  • Ansible's Verbosity: You can increase Ansible's verbosity by adding the --verbose or -v flag to the ansible_local provisioner in your Vagrantfile. This will provide more detailed output.
  • SSH into the ansible-controller: You can SSH into the ansible-controller VM after provisioning is complete to check the logs and status of the Kubernetes cluster.
    • vagrant ssh ansible-controller
    • journalctl -u kubelet (to check kubelet logs)
    • kubectl get nodes (to check the status of the nodes)
    • kubectl get pods --all-namespaces (to check pod status)

In summary:

  • The playbook.yml runs automatically as part of vagrant up, due to the ansible_local provisioner.
  • Vagrant's provisioning order and Ansible's internal dependency handling ensure that the playbook runs after the necessary prerequisites are met.
  • You can monitor the playbook's execution through Vagrant's output and by SSHing into the ansible-controller VM.

also dont see you running playbook.yaml in k8s master worker

You are absolutely right to point that out. The playbook.yml is only intended to run on the ansible-controller VM. It is not designed to run on the k8s-master or k8s-worker nodes.

Here's a breakdown of why and what the playbook.yml is supposed to do:

Purpose of playbook.yml:

  • Kubernetes Cluster Orchestration: The playbook.yml file contains Ansible tasks that automate the setup and configuration of the Kubernetes cluster.
  • Remote Execution: Ansible is designed to execute commands and tasks on remote systems (in this case, the k8s-master and k8s-worker nodes) from a central control node (the ansible-controller).
  • Centralized Configuration: The ansible-controller acts as the central point for managing the Kubernetes cluster, eliminating the need to manually execute commands on each node.

Why playbook.yml Doesn't Run on Master/Workers:

  • Ansible's Architecture: Ansible uses SSH to connect to remote systems and execute tasks. The ansible-controller VM is configured to connect to the k8s-master and k8s-worker VMs.
  • Remote Commands: The tasks in the playbook.yml file contain commands that are executed on the k8s-master and k8s-worker VMs remotely.
  • Centralized Control: Running the playbook on the master and workers would defeat the purpose of using Ansible for centralized configuration management.

What the playbook.yml Does:

  • Initializes the Kubernetes master node (kubeadm init).
  • Retrieves the kubeadm join command from the master node.
  • Joins the worker nodes to the cluster (kubeadm join).
  • Installs a network plugin (e.g., Calico) on the master node.
  • Copies the kubeconfig file from the master node to the ansible controller.

In summary:

  • The playbook.yml is executed on the ansible-controller VM.
  • The ansible-controller VM uses Ansible to remotely execute commands on the k8s-master and k8s-worker VMs.
  • This centralized approach allows for automated and consistent cluster configuration.

Therefore, you will not see the playbook running on the k8s-master or worker nodes. The ansible controller is the one that sends the commands to those nodes.

Problem:

Why This Happens:

  • The ansible playbook is being run before the k8s-master and k8s-worker nodes have been provisioned with the required kubernetes packages.
  • Incorrect Inventory: The inventory file is missing the ansible-controller entry, or the inventory file is still not being correctly parsed.
  • Vagrant Provisioning Order: Vagrant executes provisioners in the order they are defined. The ansible provisioner is running before the k8s machines are ready.

  1. Corrected Inventory File:

    • Ensure your ansible/inventory file includes the ansible-controller itself. This is important for tasks that need to run on the controller.

k8s-worker2 ansible_host=192.168.56.13

[k8s_cluster:children]
k8s_master
k8s_workers

  2. Corrected Playbook:

    • Ensure the playbook is using the correct host groups. For example, to run commands on all nodes, you can use hosts: k8s_cluster.

  3. Vagrantfile:

    • Confirm the vagrant file is the one from the previous response.

  4. Vagrant Provisioning Order:

    • Vagrant provisions the VMs in the order they are defined in the Vagrantfile.

    • Vagrant handles this automatically.

    • SSH into ansible-controller:
      • Use vagrant ssh ansible-controller to access the VM.
      • Verify the file contents with cat /vagrant/ansible/inventory.

  • Ansible needs a valid inventory to know which hosts to target.
  • Vagrant's provisioning order is crucial for ensuring that the Ansible playbook runs after the Kubernetes nodes are ready.

  1. Double-Check Inventory File Contents:

    • Exact Match: Ensure your ansible/inventory file has the following content exactly:

      Ini, TOML
      [ansible_controller]
ansible-controller ansible_host=192.168.56.10

[k8s_master]
k8s-master ansible_host=192.168.56.11

[k8s_workers]
k8s-worker1 ansible_host=192.168.56.12
k8s-worker2 ansible_host=192.168.56.13

[k8s_cluster:children]
k8s_master
k8s_workers

    • No Extra Spaces/Characters: Remove any leading/trailing spaces or invisible characters.

    • File Encoding: Verify that the file encoding is UTF-8.

  2. Verify Inventory File Location:

    • Ensure the inventory file is located in the /vagrant/ansible directory within the ansible-controller VM. This is where the ansible_local provisioner expects it.

  3. File Permissions:

    • SSH into the ansible-controller VM using vagrant ssh ansible-controller.
    • Use ls -l /vagrant/ansible/inventory to verify the file permissions. The inventory file should be readable by the vagrant user. If not, use sudo chmod 644 /vagrant/ansible/inventory.

  4. Simple Ansible Test (Inside the VM):

    • While SSH'd into the ansible-controller VM, run a simple Ansible command to test if Ansible can parse the inventory:

      Bash
      ansible all -i /vagrant/ansible/inventory -m ping

    • If you see "ping SUCCESS" messages, it means Ansible can parse the inventory. If you see errors, they will provide more information.

  5. Check Playbook Host Names:

    • Ensure that the host names in your ansible/playbook.yml file match the group names in your ansible/inventory file.

    • For example:

      YAML
      - hosts: k8s_master
  become: true
  tasks:
    # ...

  6. Vagrantfile (Already Correct):

    • Ensure that your Vagrantfile contains the code provided in the previous response.

  7. Restart Vagrant:

    • Run vagrant destroy -f and then vagrant up again to ensure all changes take effect.

Most Common Causes:

  • Typo in Inventory: A simple typo in the inventory file is the most frequent cause.
  • Incorrect File Location: The inventory file not being in /vagrant/ansible.
  • File Permissions: The inventory file not being readable by the Ansible user.

By systematically checking these points, you should be able to pinpoint the problem and get Ansible to correctly parse your inventory.

is there extention to inventory file

Yes, Ansible inventory files can have extensions. While the most common and default is just inventory (without an extension), Ansible also supports other formats and extensions.  

Here's a breakdown:

Common Inventory File Formats and Extensions:

  1. INI Format (No Extension or .ini):

    • This is the most common and default format.
    • It's a simple text file with groups and hosts defined using square brackets and key-value pairs.
    • Examples:
      • inventory
      • hosts
      • inventory.ini

  2. YAML Format (.yml or .yaml):

    • Ansible also supports YAML format for inventory files.  
    • This format is more structured and allows for more complex inventory definitions.
    • Examples:
      • inventory.yml
      • hosts.yaml

  3. Dynamic Inventory Scripts (Any Executable Extension):

    • Ansible allows you to use executable scripts (e.g., Python, Bash) to dynamically generate inventory.  
    • These scripts can fetch host information from external sources like cloud providers or databases.
    • The extension can be anything that's executable (e.g., .py, .sh).
    • Ansible will execute the script and parse its output as inventory.

How Ansible Determines the Format:

  • Ansible attempts to automatically detect the format based on the file extension.
  • If no extension is provided, or the extension is .ini, it defaults to the INI format.
  • If the extension is .yml or .yaml, it parses it as YAML.
  • If the file is executable, it runs the script.

Example of a YAML Inventory File:

YAML
all:
  hosts:
    k8s-master:
      ansible_host: 192.168.56.11
    k8s-worker1:
      ansible_host: 192.168.56.12
    k8s-worker2:
      ansible_host: 192.168.56.13
  children:
    k8s_cluster:
      children:
        k8s_master:
        k8s_workers:
    ansible_controller:
      hosts:
        ansible-controller:
          ansible_host: 192.168.56.10

Recommendation:

  • For simple inventories, the INI format (no extension or .ini) is perfectly fine.
  • For more complex inventories with nested groups or variables, YAML can be more readable and maintainable.
  • Dynamic inventory scripts are useful for large or dynamic environments.

In your current Vagrant setup, using the INI format (the default inventory file) is sufficient. Just make very sure that the contents of that file are correct.
